<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900703-0077</DOCNO><DOCID>900703-0077.</DOCID><HL>   International:   Norway Oil Union Accepts   Oslo's Back-to-Work Order   ----   Special to The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>07/03/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   LABOR EUROP</CO><IN>PETROLEUM (PET)</IN><LP>   OSLO -- A Norwegian oil workers' union said it resolved toaccept a government back-to-work order yesterday but did notexclude the possibility of wildcat strikes on offshoreplatforms.   The central committee of the Norwegian Federation of OilWorkers advised 4,000 striking workers to return to workbecause compulsory arbitration ordered by the governmentearlier yesterday is legally binding, said deputy leaderOddleiv Tonnessen.</LP><TEXT>   The union had considered defying the government order,claiming it violates international trade union agreements.   A union official, speaking unofficially, said unsanctionedwildcat strikes might break out at some offshore fields.   The 6,000 member union began shutting Norway's North Seaproduction of 1.63 million barrels a day of oil and 63billion cubic feet a month of natural gas at midnightSaturday. Last-minute negotiations had failed to settle a newcontract.</TEXT></DOC>